## Security & Error Handling Review

### 1. 🔴 Missing Security Headers
The app has no security headers, making it vulnerable to clickjacking, MIME sniffing, and XSS attacks. Add `helmet`:
```js
const helmet = require('helmet');
app.use(helmet());
```

### 2. 🔴 No Rate Limiting
Both endpoints are wide open to abuse/DoS. Add rate limiting:
```js
const rateLimit = require('express-rate-limit');
const limiter = rateLimit({ windowMs: 15 * 60 * 1000, max: 100 });
app.use(limiter);
```

### 3. 🔴 No Global Error Handler
Unhandled errors will leak stack traces (revealing file paths, library versions, etc.). Add a global error handler **as the last middleware**:
```js
// Catch-all 404
app.use((req, res, next) => {
  res.status(404).json({ error: 'Not found' });
});

// Global error handler — never expose err.stack in production
app.use((err, req, res, next) => {
  console.error(err); // log internally
  const status = err.status || 500;
  const message = process.env.NODE_ENV === 'production'
    ? 'Internal server error'
    : err.message;
  res.status(status).json({ error: message });
});
```

### 4. 🟡 No Request Body Parsing Middleware
Without this, POST/PUT bodies are silently ignored — and if added later without size limits, it's a DoS vector:
```js
app.use(express.json({ limit: '10kb' }));
app.use(express.urlencoded({ extended: true, limit: '10kb' }));
```

### 5. 🟡 `/users` Exposes PII Without Auth
User emails are returned to any caller without authentication. At minimum, add an auth middleware stub and note this must be protected:
```js
// Require auth before any /users route
app.use('/users', requireAuth); // implement with JWT or session check

app.get('/users', (req, res, next) => {
  try {
    // In real app: fetch from DB, handle errors
    res.json([...]);
  } catch (err) {
    next(err); // passes to global error handler
  }
});
```

### 6. 🟡 No Input Validation on Query Parameters
If `/users` gains filtering (e.g., `?id=1`), unsanitized params could enable injection. Use a validator from the start:
```js
